---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import ToolReview from '../../components/ToolReview.astro';
import { site, description } from '../../content';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const path = '/guides/deliverability';
const title = 'Shopify Email Deliverability Guide: 13 Tools and a Safer Pilot';
const desc = description(site, 'guides/deliverability');

const tools = [
  { slug: 'klaviyo', best: 'behavioral Shopify lifecycle programs', pros: 'Deep event, catalog, and consent controls', cons: 'Profile-based pricing and configuration overhead', pricing: 'Verify current active-profile, email, and SMS tiers', url: 'https://www.klaviyo.com/pricing', paragraphs: ['Klaviyo is a strong fit when Shopify events, product data, and consent state need to drive separate welcome, browse, cart, post-purchase, and replenishment paths. For deliverability, the useful work is operational: map Shopify order and fulfillment events, exclude recent purchasers from acquisition messages, and review bounce, unsubscribe, and complaint trends by flow rather than trusting one blended store rate.', 'Pilot one catalog-aware flow and one campaign segment. Confirm that guest checkout, subscription, refund, and regional consent fields arrive as expected; then compare a holdout or matched group on delivered orders, complaints, unsubscribes, and margin. Its deliverability tools can support diagnosis, but they do not make a cold import or a high-frequency send safe.'] },
  { slug: 'omnisend', best: 'fast ecommerce email and SMS journeys', pros: 'Shopify-oriented templates and event triggers', cons: 'Cross-channel frequency needs explicit governance', pricing: 'Verify current contact, send, and SMS limits', url: 'https://www.omnisend.com/pricing/', paragraphs: ['Omnisend suits a store that wants ready-made ecommerce journeys around Shopify browsing, cart, purchase, and product activity. The deliverability question is whether the team can keep email and SMS ownership clear: a cart reminder, replenishment message, and sale broadcast should share suppression logic so the same customer does not receive overlapping incentives.', 'Start with a single email welcome or cart journey, purchaser suppression, and a quiet-period rule for concurrent SMS. Check event latency, unsubscribe propagation, hard-bounce handling, and whether product links still resolve after catalog changes. Treat any plan limits and channel pricing as changeable; confirm them on the vendor page before budgeting.'] },
  { slug: 'shopify-email', best: 'simple broadcasts inside Shopify Admin', pros: 'Native store context and low operational friction', cons: 'Less lifecycle depth than specialist platforms', pricing: 'Verify current Shopify plan, send, and feature limits', url: 'https://www.shopify.com/email', paragraphs: ['Shopify Email is the least complicated place to start when a merchant mainly needs consented broadcasts, product links, and basic customer targeting in the Shopify admin. Native context reduces integration handoffs, but it does not remove the need to authenticate the sending domain, honor unsubscribes, remove recent purchasers where appropriate, and watch bounces and complaints.', 'Pilot a product announcement to an engaged, consented segment, with a small internal seed list and a no-send control if the store can support one. Confirm the footer, unsubscribe path, sender identity, audience exclusions, and image rendering before expanding. Move only when the store can name a specific missing workflow; do not assume a larger platform automatically improves inbox placement.'] },
  { slug: 'brevo', best: 'email, SMS, and transactional separation on a lean stack', pros: 'Broad channel coverage and SMTP/transactional options', cons: 'Shopify event depth may require careful mapping', pricing: 'Verify current send, contact, SMS, and transactional pricing', url: 'https://www.brevo.com/pricing/', paragraphs: ['Brevo can be useful when a Shopify store needs marketing email alongside transactional infrastructure or additional channels. The deliverability boundary matters: order confirmations and shipping updates should be owned by an operational message path, while promotions should have their own consent, suppression, and reporting rules. Document which system sends each message before connecting both to the same store.', 'Pilot one marketing flow with Shopify purchase suppression and one transactional template, then inspect headers, event timing, unsubscribe behavior, bounce classification, and reply handling. Do not infer reputation quality from a platform feature list. Confirm current pricing and whether the integrations expose the Shopify fields your flows need.'] },
  { slug: 'mailchimp', best: 'familiar campaign workflows for smaller catalogs', pros: 'Mature campaign editor and broad ecosystem', cons: 'Data synchronization and audience hygiene need attention', pricing: 'Verify current contact, send, and feature tiers', url: 'https://mailchimp.com/pricing/', paragraphs: ['Mailchimp remains a reasonable candidate for campaign-led stores that need a familiar editor and standard audience operations. Shopify deliverability depends on the connector and audience model: verify that purchase, refund, consent, and unsubscribe state are synchronized before using customer segments for cart, winback, or post-purchase messages.', 'Pilot a newsletter to a recent-engager segment and a separate purchaser exclusion. Check duplicate profiles, imported unsubscribes, hard-bounce suppression, and whether a customer who buys after scheduling is removed from the promotion. Pricing is audience-shaped and product terms can change, so use the official pricing page rather than a remembered threshold.'] },
  { slug: 'activecampaign', best: 'CRM-style lifecycle logic around Shopify events', pros: 'Flexible automation and contact attributes', cons: 'More moving parts than a broadcast-first stack', pricing: 'Verify current contact, feature, and add-on pricing', url: 'https://www.activecampaign.com/pricing', paragraphs: ['ActiveCampaign is relevant when Shopify activity must join a broader CRM or sales process, such as high-consideration products, wholesale leads, or service follow-up. Deliverability depends on designing a single source of truth for consent and message ownership; a CRM automation should not keep mailing someone after a Shopify unsubscribe, refund, or support escalation.', 'Run a pilot with one purchase-triggered education sequence and an explicit marketing-consent gate. Test duplicate contact merging, tag removal, transactional-versus-promotional classification, and the stop conditions that end the sequence. Evaluate incremental repeat orders and complaints, not automation count. Confirm current plan requirements before treating a feature as included.'] },
  { slug: 'drip', best: 'commerce-focused lifecycle segmentation', pros: 'Ecommerce-oriented customer and revenue context', cons: 'Smaller teams still need event and suppression QA', pricing: 'Verify current subscriber and send pricing', url: 'https://www.drip.com/pricing', paragraphs: ['Drip is designed around ecommerce customer behavior, which can help Shopify teams build segments for first purchase, repeat purchase, product category, and post-purchase education. Those signals are only useful for deliverability when event freshness and consent are tested; a stale order event can send a replenishment or cross-sell message at exactly the wrong time.', 'Pilot one replenishment or product-education sequence with a recent-purchaser exclusion and a short holdout. Confirm cancellation, refund, out-of-stock, and unsubscribe behavior, then inspect delivered, bounced, complained, and unsubscribed cohorts. Use the official pricing page for the current subscriber model and avoid assuming that revenue attribution equals incremental revenue.'] },
  { slug: 'sendlane', best: 'DTC lifecycle automation with hands-on operations', pros: 'Lifecycle-focused controls and ecommerce orientation', cons: 'Smaller teams should validate integration coverage early', pricing: 'Verify current contacts, sends, and onboarding terms', url: 'https://www.sendlane.com/pricing', paragraphs: ['Sendlane is a candidate for DTC merchants that want lifecycle automation around Shopify behavior without treating every broadcast as a separate project. Review the actual event contract for products, orders, refunds, and consent; a named integration is not evidence that every field needed by a suppression rule is available.', 'Pilot welcome, cart, and post-purchase ownership as three separate paths, with one documented collision priority. Verify one-click unsubscribe, bounce suppression, cart expiry, and purchase-based exits with test orders. Confirm current pricing and any onboarding or volume requirements directly with the vendor before committing.'] },
  { slug: 'yotpo-email-sms', best: 'email and SMS alongside reviews or loyalty context', pros: 'Potentially useful shared customer context across channels', cons: 'Email reputation still needs separate monitoring', pricing: 'Verify current email, SMS, contact, and bundle pricing', url: 'https://www.yotpo.com/pricing/', paragraphs: ['Yotpo Email & SMS is most relevant when a Shopify merchant already operates Yotpo customer-content or loyalty surfaces and wants those signals near messaging. Deliverability work should focus on channel collision: review requests, loyalty reminders, replenishment, and promotions need one suppression map, especially after a customer has purchased or opted out of a channel.', 'Pilot a post-purchase review request with a clear service-versus-marketing classification, then test a promotional follow-up only for customers who remain eligible. Inspect consent records, purchase exits, SMS opt-outs, email unsubscribes, and template links. Treat bundled pricing as variable and validate the current plan, channel fees, and integration behavior before migration.'] },
  { slug: 'privy', best: 'onsite capture feeding a primary sender', pros: 'Capture context can improve welcome relevance', cons: 'Not a substitute for a full lifecycle owner', pricing: 'Verify current contacts, sends, SMS, and feature limits', url: 'https://www.privy.com/pricing', paragraphs: ['Privy is primarily useful at the capture edge of a Shopify stack: popup, form, offer, or onsite intent can provide context for a relevant welcome program. The deliverability risk is duplicate ownership. Decide which platform sends the welcome, which system stores consent, and how the capture tool stops sending after purchase or unsubscribe.', 'Pilot one capture source with a non-discount welcome variant and a purchaser suppression rule. Confirm consent language, country rules, duplicate handling, handoff timing, and whether the destination ESP receives source and timestamp fields. Measure qualified subscribers and downstream complaints, not popup conversion alone; verify current pricing before calculating payback.'] },
  { slug: 'postscript', best: 'SMS-led Shopify retention with email kept distinct', pros: 'Strong fit for SMS-first store workflows', cons: 'Email deliverability is not solved by SMS reach', pricing: 'Verify current SMS, contact, and message pricing', url: 'https://postscript.io/pricing', paragraphs: ['Postscript is an SMS specialist, so its Shopify deliverability value is mostly about disciplined channel separation. A store can use it for consented SMS around launches or cart recovery while leaving email to an ESP, but the two systems still need shared purchase, suppression, quiet-hour, and discount-collision rules.', 'Pilot one SMS journey with email excluded from the same customer window. Test opt-out propagation, purchase cancellation, international consent, link behavior, and frequency caps. Judge the combined customer experience and margin, not SMS clicks in isolation. Confirm current messaging costs and carrier or compliance requirements from the official source.'] },
  { slug: 'attentive', best: 'enterprise SMS and lifecycle orchestration', pros: 'Advanced consent and channel operations for larger teams', cons: 'Higher operational and commercial complexity', pricing: 'Request a current quote; terms vary by volume and scope', url: 'https://www.attentive.com/pricing', paragraphs: ['Attentive is relevant to larger Shopify programs where SMS consent, lifecycle orchestration, and governance require dedicated ownership. It should be evaluated as part of a channel architecture, not as a promise of inbox placement. Email authentication, suppression, and complaint monitoring remain responsibilities of the system sending email.', 'Pilot one Shopify event-led journey with clear email/SMS handoff and a control group. Verify consent capture, opt-out synchronization, purchase exits, regional rules, quiet hours, and support escalation before adding more journeys. Commercial terms are commonly quote-based; obtain a current proposal and document what is included.'] },
  { slug: 'sendgrid', best: 'developer-owned transactional and email infrastructure', pros: 'Flexible APIs and operational sending controls', cons: 'Requires engineering and a separate lifecycle layer', pricing: 'Verify current email API, marketing, and support pricing', url: 'https://sendgrid.com/en-us/pricing', paragraphs: ['SendGrid fits teams that need developer-owned delivery for transactional messages, custom applications, or a controlled email API. For Shopify, the key decision is message ownership: order and account events can use an API path while marketing journeys remain in a consent-aware lifecycle platform. Avoid putting promotional and operational logic into one ungoverned stream.', 'Pilot one low-risk transactional event and inspect authentication alignment, headers, bounce webhooks, suppression groups, and template fallback behavior. Keep marketing consent and unsubscribe state available to any promotional sender. Validate current product limits and deliverability support terms; an API gives control, not automatic placement.'] },
  { slug: 'tinyemail', best: 'small stores testing simple ecommerce campaigns', pros: 'Low-friction campaign setup for basic needs', cons: 'Validate depth of Shopify events and reporting', pricing: 'Verify current subscriber, send, and feature limits', url: 'https://tinyemail.com/pricing', paragraphs: ['tinyEmail can be considered by a small Shopify store that needs straightforward campaigns and basic automation. The deliverability review should be practical: confirm domain authentication, Shopify event coverage, consent import behavior, bounce handling, and whether customers can be excluded after purchase before adding urgency or winback campaigns.', 'Run a contained pilot to recent engagers with a product link, an unsubscribe check, and a purchaser exclusion. Review delivery, hard bounces, complaints, unsubscribes, and revenue per delivered message against a comparable send. Pricing and included automation levels can change, so verify them on the official page.'] },
];

const featuredApps = tools.map((tool) => ({ ...tool, app: appBySlug(tool.slug)! })).filter((tool) => tool.app);

const faqs = [
  { question: 'What should a Shopify store measure first?', answer: 'Start with delivery, hard bounces, spam complaints, unsubscribes, clicks, and delivered revenue by domain and flow. Opens are directional because privacy features can distort them.' },
  { question: 'Does changing platforms automatically improve deliverability?', answer: 'No. A migration can preserve or damage reputation depending on authentication, consent, suppression history, event mapping, and volume ramp. Test an engaged segment before moving the whole file.' },
  { question: 'Should transactional and marketing email use the same stream?', answer: 'Keep ownership and classification explicit. Order and account messages need operational controls; promotions need marketing consent and easy unsubscribe. A shared domain can be workable, but the decision should be documented and monitored.' },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24"><div class="container"><a href="/guides" class="text-sm font-bold text-[#9a5b16]">← All operator guides</a><p class="catalog-kicker mt-6">Deliverability</p><h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Shopify email deliverability: choose the control surface, then prove it</h1><p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">Inbox placement is an operating system, not a vendor badge. Shopify order state, consent, catalog changes, fulfillment timing, message frequency, authentication, and complaint handling all meet in the inbox.</p><p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">This guide compares 13 relevant tools. It uses evidence-safe language: verify current features, pricing, integration fields, and sending terms in each official source before purchase or migration.</p><div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3"><a class="btn btn-primary" href="/guides/migration">Migration playbook</a><a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/guides/consent-compliance">Consent guide</a><a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/use-cases/deliverability">Deliverability use case</a></div></div></section>

  <section class="container pb-12"><TldrBox title="Deliverability operating principles" picks={[{ label: 'Authenticate', tool: 'SPF, DKIM, DMARC', reason: 'Verify alignment before sending meaningful volume.' }, { label: 'Segment', tool: 'Consent + engagement', reason: 'Start with customers who have a current reason to receive the message.' }, { label: 'Suppress', tool: 'Purchases, opt-outs, collisions', reason: 'Make one system responsible for stop conditions.' }, { label: 'Ramp', tool: 'Small controlled pilot', reason: 'Increase volume only after delivery and complaint signals are understood.' }, { label: 'Measure', tool: 'Delivered revenue and complaints', reason: 'Use clicks and downstream orders alongside privacy-affected opens.' }]} />
    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12"><h2>Shopify-specific risks to inspect</h2><p>Guest checkout can create duplicate or typo-prone profiles. Subscription, refund, cancellation, and fulfillment events can arrive on different timelines. Product feeds change when variants go out of stock. A browse or cart flow that ignores those states can send irrelevant messages, increase complaints, and create support load even when the email technically delivers.</p><p>Before comparing dashboards, draw message ownership: who sends the order confirmation, shipping update, review request, cart reminder, replenishment notice, and promotion? Then map consent, unsubscribe, purchase suppression, bounce handling, and frequency limits across every system that can contact the customer.</p></div>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto"><table><thead><tr><th>Shopify signal</th><th>Deliverability control</th><th>Evidence to verify in a pilot</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Order, refund, cancellation</td><td>Exit or suppress promotional journeys</td><td>Test order state changes and event timing</td></tr><tr><td>Consent and channel preference</td><td>Honor source, region, unsubscribe, and SMS opt-out</td><td>Export timestamps and test each preference path</td></tr><tr><td>Product, inventory, variant</td><td>Prevent broken or irrelevant dynamic content</td><td>Preview out-of-stock and changed-URL cases</td></tr><tr><td>Engagement and complaints</td><td>Limit cold-segment volume and investigate spikes</td><td>Review by flow, domain, and cohort—not one blended rate</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
  </section>

  <section class="container space-y-12 pb-16"><p class="catalog-kicker">Platform comparison</p><h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">13 tools for different Shopify jobs</h2><div class="overflow-x-auto"><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Best for</th><th>Pros</th><th>Cons</th><th>Pricing caveat</th></tr></thead><tbody>{tools.map((tool) => <tr><td><a class="link" href={tool.url} rel="nofollow">{appBySlug(tool.slug)?.name}</a></td><td>{tool.best}</td><td>{tool.pros}</td><td>{tool.cons}</td><td>{tool.pricing}</td></tr>)}</tbody></table></div>{featuredApps.map((tool, index) => <ToolReview app={tool.app} rank={index + 1} paragraphs={tool.paragraphs} />)}</section>

  <section class="container py-12"><div class="ledger-card"><p class="catalog-kicker">Implementation pilot</p><h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">A 14-day evidence-first test</h2><div class="prose-shopify mt-5"><p><strong>Days 1–3:</strong> inventory every sender and flow; document Shopify events, consent source, authentication status, suppression owner, and current pricing assumptions. Create a seed list across Gmail, Outlook, Yahoo, and Apple Mail where practical.</p><p><strong>Days 4–7:</strong> connect one low-risk flow to a recent-engager segment. Place test orders, refunds, cancellations, and unsubscribes. Confirm that purchase exits, links, product data, headers, and preference changes behave as designed.</p><p><strong>Days 8–14:</strong> send a controlled campaign with a matched holdout when possible. Record delivered messages, hard bounces, complaints, unsubscribes, clicks, support contacts, delivered revenue, discounts, refunds, and app cost. Expand only when the team can explain every stop condition.</p></div></div></section>

  <section class="container py-12"><div class="prose-shopify"><h2>Authentication and monitoring checklist</h2><ul><li>SPF, DKIM, and DMARC are configured for the actual sending domain or subdomain.</li><li>From address, reply handling, unsubscribe, and one-click list-unsubscribe behavior are tested.</li><li>Marketing and transactional ownership is documented, including suppression and reply escalation.</li><li>Hard bounces, complaints, unsubscribes, and delivery by mailbox domain are reviewed by flow.</li><li>New domains, platforms, and major volume changes use an engaged-first ramp rather than a full-list blast.</li><li>Gmail Postmaster Tools, Microsoft SNDS where applicable, and ESP logs are treated as diagnostic inputs—not universal benchmarks.</li></ul><p>Official references: <a class="link" href="https://support.google.com/a/answer/81126">Google sender guidelines</a>, <a class="link" href="https://senders.yahooinc.com/best-practices/">Yahoo sender best practices</a>, and <a class="link" href="https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/dns/dns-records/dns-spf-record/">SPF background</a>. Requirements and product behavior can change; check the source when implementing.</p></div></section>

  <section class="container py-12"><div class="overflow-x-auto"><table><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Prefer when</th><th>Do not infer</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Native Shopify campaign tool</td><td>Broadcast needs are simple and store context matters</td><td>Native means stronger inbox placement</td></tr><tr><td>Lifecycle platform</td><td>Many Shopify events need governed journeys</td><td>More automation means more incremental revenue</td></tr><tr><td>Capture or SMS specialist</td><td>A distinct channel job needs dedicated controls</td><td>Another channel repairs email reputation</td></tr><tr><td>Developer-owned infrastructure</td><td>Transactional or custom application delivery needs APIs</td><td>API control replaces consent and monitoring</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section>

  <section class="container py-12"><FaqSection faqs={faqs} /></section>
  <section class="container pb-12"><div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm font-bold"><a class="link" href="/guides">All guides →</a><a class="link" href="/guides/migration">Migration →</a><a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">Selection framework →</a></div></section>
</BaseLayout>
